# CODEN v1
# title: Coden System Builder

## Instructions
You are helping me build and refine my CODEN topic-file system.

Goals:
- One .coden file per topic
- Persistent conversation saved inside the file
- Looping interactive terminal session until :exit
- Clean streaming output using Codex CLI
- Production-ready and future-proof architecture
- Windows-focused implementation

When discussing implementation:
- Prefer stable CLI flags
- Avoid relying on undocumented JSON schemas
- Keep file format human-editable
- Optimize for long-running topics with rolling summaries

## Pinned
- I am using Windows.
- I have Node.js 18+ installed.
- Codex CLI is installed and available as `codex`.
- Topic files use the `.coden` extension.
- The Node wrapper is `coden.mjs`.
- File association handled by `coden-setup.bat`.
- Default sandbox mode is read-only.
- I prefer streaming responses in the terminal.

## Summary

- User is building a Windows-first persistent topic chat system using `.coden` files, with production-ready and future-proof behavior as a priority.
- `.coden` structure is stable: `Instructions`, `Pinned`, `Summary`, and `Conversation`; each topic is one file with rolling summary updates.
- Core runtime is a Node wrapper (`coden.mjs`) around `codex exec --json --output-last-message -`, with lock-file protection and atomic/safe file updates.
- Custom loop/ops commands include `:exit`, `:model`, `:tail`, `:fork`, `:export`, and `:summary`; startup now shows available commands every load.
- Key parser/control fixes were made: invalid regex end-anchor behavior corrected, conversation block parsing improved, and `:summary` handled as a control command (not sent as user prompt).
- Startup behavior now differentiates empty vs non-empty topics:
  - Empty `.coden`: prompts for minimal instructions, then initializes required sections.
  - Non-empty `.coden`: shows instruction/conversation snapshot on load.
- Folder-level shared instructions support was added with default `AGENTS.md` (Codex CLI convention), plus fallback to `agent.md`; these instructions are injected each turn and shown at startup.
- Snapshot display order on load is now: folder-level instructions first, then topic instructions, then recent conversation.
- User preference changed back to default sandbox write capability in the topic folder context (`workspace-write`), after a temporary read-only default caused friction.
- Operational context: project folder is `C:\Mine\Coden`; user can run commands and perform git actions manually; assistant provided manual git add/commit/push instructions for integrating changes.

